description.narrative:
General question: Results related to the intended outcome 2015Question: Summarise results related to the intended outcome (this information will be sent to Open Aid)Answer: The results targets specified in the original results framework was largely achieved. Key achievements in 2013-2016 include: 
a. Piloted processes for mainstreaming climate change adaptation in sub-national planning;
b. Demonstrated that, given the resources, sub-national administrations have the capacity to
plan and implement climate change adaptation projects;
c. Built capacity of sub-national administrations for climate change adaptation through a
combination of formal training and “learning by doing”.
d. 7 Districts and 1 Municipality received a Performance Based Climate Resilience Grant (PBCRG)
allocation each year for 3 years;
e. LGCC-2 funds were amongst the first donor funds executed through the District budget;
f. Total grant allocation was $1,040,000
g. Developed a performance assessment system including an index of climate change adaptation
mainstreaming capacity of SNAs;
h. 80% of grants ($827,371) allocated to projects;
i. Co-financing from the Commune-Sangkat Fund was $1,550,625;
j. 57 Communes (out of 61 in the target Districts) received financing for projects from the PBCRG
resources;
k. 50 rural roads in flood-prone areas climate-proofed;
l. 29 small-scale climate adaptive irrigation schemes;
m. 8 climate adaptive rural water supplies schemes;
n. 10 flood protection and drainage schemes;
o. 68 training and other non-infrastructure projects implemented
p. Total project beneficiaries estimated as about 900,000 (410,000 female).
q. New guidelines for sub-national development planning integrate climate change adaptation
planning procedures piloted under LGCC
r. Encouraged additional donors (IFAD, UNDP-GEF) to implement the Performance Based
Climate Resilience Grant model.

UNCDF and NCDD requested a no cost extention for the period January-June 2016. During the no cost extension phase all the intended outcomes were largely achieved. 

The following activities were achieved in 2016:
- All 27 climate adaptive infrastructure projects were fully completed. This included i.a. support to 7 districts, 1 municipality and 57 communes for 50 rural roads, 29 climate adaptive irrigation schemes, 8 water supplies schemes and 10  flood protection and drainage schemes. 
- Eleven out of fifteen non-infrastructure Projects were completed.
- NCDD-s was nominated to become an National Implementing  Entity under the Global Climate Fund. 
- The Performance Asseesment system was revised and improved. 
- LGCC continued supporting the mainstreaming of CCA in sub-national planning guidelines. 

The project was successful in mobilizing co-funding from the government DM and CS funds, and put procedures in place for scaling up climate adaptive investments.
